# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1968-red-square-demonstration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In late February 1948, the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia (KSČ), with Soviet backing, assumed undisputed control over the government of Czechoslovakia through a coup d'état.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] It marked the beginning of four decades of the party's rule in the country.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The KSČ enjoyed a period of popularity following the reestablishment of pre-war Czechoslovakia.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] After a successful performance during the 1946 parliamentary election, party leader Klement Gottwald became prime minister of a coalition government at the behest of President Edvard Beneš.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] By summer 1947, however, the KSČ's popularity had significantly dwindled, and the party was expected to be soundly defeated in the May 1948 elections.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] This, along with the electoral failures of the French and Italian communist parties, prompted Joseph Stalin to harden his approach and order Gottwald to seize power.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 21 February 1948, twelve non-Communist ministers resigned in protest.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] They objected to Gottwald's refusal to stop packing the police with Communists, and believed that Gottwald would give way.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Instead, he threatened a general strike unless Beneš appointed a Communist-dominated government.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Armed Communist militia and police took over Prague and mass demonstrations were mounted.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 25 February, Beneš, fearing civil war and Soviet intervention, capitulated and allowed the formation of a new government in accordance with KSČ demands.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] While ostensibly a coalition, it was dominated by Communists and fellow travellers.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The Communists quickly consolidated their power following the coup.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The National Assembly approved a new constitution on 9 May, declaring Czechoslovakia a "people's democratic state".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The 30 May elections, in which voters were presented with a single list of candidates, all but confirmed the Communist victory.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Beneš resigned on 2 June and was succeeded by Gottwald as president.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The coup's significance extended well beyond the state's boundaries as it was a clear marker along the already well-advanced road to full-fledged Cold War.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In the aftermath of World War II, the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia (KSČ) was in a favorable position.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Moreover, the Soviets viewed the country as a strategic prize: it bordered West Germany and boasted uranium deposits around Jáchymov.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] During the early postwar period, working with the other parties in a coalition called the National Front, the Communists kept up the appearance of being willing to work within the system.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Thus, in the 1946 election, the KSČ and KSS won 38% of the vote.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] This was the best-ever performance by a European Communist party in a free election, and was far more than the 22% won by their Hungarian counterparts the following year in the only other free and fair postwar election in the Soviet area of influence.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] President Edvard Beneš, not himself a Communist but very amenable to cooperation with the Soviets, and who hoped for restraint by the Allied powers, thus invited Gottwald to be prime minister.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, by the summer of 1947 the KSČ had alienated whole blocs of potential voters.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The activities of the police—headed by Interior Minister Václav Nosek, a Communist—were acutely offensive to many citizens; farmers objected to talk of collectivization, and some workers were angry at Communist demands that they increase output without being given higher wages.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The general expectation was that the Communists would be soundly defeated in the May 1948 elections.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] That notion would be reinforced during the Prague Spring, when party archives were opened and showed that Stalin gave up the whole idea of a parliamentary path for Czechoslovakia when the Communist parties of France and Italy failed to achieve power in 1947 and 1948.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The KSČ's number-two leader, general secretary Rudolf Slánský, represented the KSČ at the meeting.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He returned to Prague with a plan for the final seizure of power.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Slánský remarked, "as in the international field, we have gone on the offensive on the domestic front as well." The KSČ pursued a two-pronged strategy.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The party knew it had to maintain the façade of working within the electoral political system and was aware that a revolutionary coup would be unacceptable.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] It desired to gain an absolute majority at elections scheduled for 1948, but the fracturing of the left-wing coalition made this unrealistic.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] This pushed the party into extra-parliamentary action.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The organization of "spontaneous" demonstrations to "express the will of the people" and continuous visits to parliament by workers' delegations were meant to ensure "mobilization of the masses".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] During the winter of 1947–48, both in the cabinet and in parliament tension between the Communists and their opponents led to increasingly bitter conflict.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Matters came to a head in February 1948, when Nosek illegally extended his powers by attempting to purge remaining non-Communist elements in the National Police Force.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The security apparatus and police were being transformed into instruments of the KSČ, and consequently, according to John Grenville, endangering basic civic freedoms.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 12 February, the non-Communists in the cabinet demanded punishment for the offending Communists in the government and an end to their supposed subversion.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Nosek, backed by Gottwald, refused to yield.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He and his fellow Communists threatened to use force and, in order to avoid defeat in parliament, mobilised groups of their supporters in the country.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 21 February, twelve non-Communist ministers resigned in protest after Nosek refused to reinstate eight non-Communist senior police officers despite a majority vote of the cabinet in favour of doing so.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Most of the ministers remained at their posts, with Social Democratic leader Zdeněk Fierlinger making no secret of his support for the Communists.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The non-Communists assumed that Beneš would refuse to accept their resignations, keeping them in a caretaker government and in the process embarrassing the Communists enough to make them yield.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Beneš initially insisted that no new government could be formed which did not include ministers from the non-Communist parties.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, an atmosphere of mounting tension, coupled with massive Communist-led demonstrations occurring throughout the country, convinced Beneš to remain neutral over the issue, for fear the KSČ foment an insurrection and give the Red Army a pretext to invade the country and restore order.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In Grenville's opinion, had Beneš held his line, the Communists would not have been able to form a government.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The historian believed there could have been only two non-violent means of resolving the crisis—give way to the non-Communists or risk defeat in early elections which the KSČ would not have had time to rig.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The non-Communists saw this as a moment of opportunity, needing to act quickly before the Communists had total control over the police and threatened the electoral process.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] At the same time, the non-Communist ministers seemed to behave as if this was just an old-fashioned pre-1939 governmental crisis.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] They did not know that the Communists were mobilizing from below to take complete power.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Soviet deputy foreign minister Valerian Zorin, who had been his country's ambassador to Czechoslovakia from 1945 to 1947, returned to Prague to help with the final arrangements for the coup.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Armed militia and police took over Prague, Communist demonstrations were mounted and an anti-Communist student demonstration was broken up.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The ministries of the non-Communist ministers were occupied, civil servants dismissed and the ministers prevented from entering their own ministries.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The army, under the direction of Defence Minister Ludvík Svoboda, who was formally non-partisan but had facilitated Communist infiltration into the officer corps, was confined to barracks and did not interfere.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Communist "Action Committees" and trade union militias were quickly set up, armed, and sent into the streets, as well as being prepared to carry through a purge of anti-Communists.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In a speech before 100,000 of these people, Gottwald threatened a general strike unless Beneš agreed to form a new Communist-dominated government.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Zorin at one point offered the services of the Red Army, camped on the country's borders.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, Gottwald declined the offer, believing that the threat of violence combined with heavy political pressure would be enough to force Beneš to surrender.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] As he said after the coup, Beneš "knows what strength is, and this led him to evaluate this [situation] realistically".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Additionally, according to historian Igor Lukes, Beneš had been in poor health since 1945, and by 1948 was "a shell of a man" who did not have the emotional or physical stamina to hold out against the "rough, rough players" of the KSČ.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 25 February 1948, Beneš, fearful of civil war and Soviet intervention, capitulated.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He accepted the resignations of the non-Communist ministers and appointed a new government in accordance with KSČ demands.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Gottwald continued as prime minister of a new government comprising 25 members–13 Communists and 12 non-Communists (nine members from non-Communist parties and three independents).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In truth, the new government was dominated by Communists and pro-Moscow Social Democrats.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The Social Democrats' leader, Fierlinger, had been a proponent of closer ties with the Communists for some time; as mentioned above, he openly sided with the Communists during the dispute.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Members of the People's, Czech National Social Party and Slovak Democratic parties still figured, so the government was still nominally a coalition.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, this was no longer a coalition in any real sense of the term.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The other parties had been taken over by fellow travellers who were loyal partners of the Communists, and ministers using these labels were handpicked by the Communists.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The only senior minister who was neither a Communist nor a fellow traveller was Foreign Minister Jan Masaryk, who was however found dead two weeks later outside a third-floor window.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Some friends and admirers believed Masaryk committed suicide out of despair.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, there was longstanding Western suspicion was that he had actually been thrown to his death, which remains to this day, with an investigation closed in 2021 ruling murder, accident, or suicide all possible.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Following the coup, the Communists moved quickly to consolidate their power.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Thousands were fired and hundreds were arrested.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Thousands fled the country to avoid living under Communism.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The National Assembly, freely elected two years earlier, quickly fell into line and gave Gottwald's revamped government a vote of confidence in March.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The 230–0 result was unanimous, although nine MPs had resigned following the coup.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 9 May, a new constitution was approved by parliament, which declared Czechoslovakia a "people's democratic state." Although it was not a completely Communist document (indeed, the KSČ was not even mentioned), it was close enough to the Soviet model that Beneš refused to sign it.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] At the 30 May elections, voters were presented with a single list from the National Front, which officially won 89.2% of the vote; within the National Front list, the Communists had an absolute majority of 214 seats (160 for the main party and 54 for the Slovak branch).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] This majority grew even larger when the Social Democrats merged with the Communists later in the year.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Practically all non-Communist parties that had participated in the 1946 election were also represented within the National Front list and thus received parliamentary seats.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, by this time they were now almost completely subservient to the Communists, and the few independent-minded members of those parties were either in prison or in exile.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The National Front was converted into a broad patriotic organisation dominated by the Communists, and no political group outside it was allowed to exist.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Consumed by these events, Beneš resigned on 2 June and was succeeded by Gottwald twelve days later.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Beneš died in September, bringing a symbolic close to the sequence of events, and was buried before an enormous and silent throng come to mourn the passing of a popular leader and of the democracy he had come to represent.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Czechoslovakia was ruled by a victorious Communist Party of Czechoslovakia until the Velvet Revolution of 1989.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] More immediately, the coup became synonymous with the Cold War.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The loss of the last remaining liberal democracy in Eastern Europe came as a profound shock to millions in the West.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] For the second time in a decade, Western eyes saw Czechoslovak independence and democracy snuffed out by a foreign totalitarian dictatorship intent on dominating the small country (though unlike in 1938–39, the KSČ did most of the "dirty work").
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Because its impact was equally profound in Western Europe as in the United States, it helped unify Western countries against the Communist bloc.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] It gave an air of prescience to the French and Italian governments for having forced their local Communists out of their governments a year earlier.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Additionally, it finally discredited Soviet moves to prevent the formation of a West German state and accelerated the construction of a West European alliance, the Treaty of Brussels, the following month; mutual security was the new watchword.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] By early March, even a previously wavering France was demanding a concrete military alliance with definite promises to help in certain circumstances.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] From the Soviet's point of view, the coup could not have come at a worse time.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The government crisis in Prague lasted from 20 to 27 February, just when Western foreign ministers were meeting in London.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] From the West's perspective, the coup was an example of Communism in its most unacceptable form; the USSR seemed to the West bent on ruthless expansion and the suppression of freedom.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The coup's impact in the United States was immediate.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Opposition towards the Marshall Plan had developed in the United States Congress, but a shocked and aroused public opinion overwhelmed this, and Congress promptly approved over US$5 billion for the first year of the European Recovery Program.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Until the Czech coup, the emphasis in Washington had been on economic containment of Communism, primarily through the Truman Doctrine and the Marshall Plan and a heavy reliance on atomic power as a shield to support it.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Truman understood that in 1946 and 1947 the American people were not prepared for a massive conventional arms buildup or a confrontation with the Soviet Union.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He was reluctant to increase the military budget dramatically and instead chose a gradual and balanced buildup.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Expecting to spend large amounts on the Marshall Plan, he sought to keep the annual defence budget below $15 billion.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, the coup served to expose the limitations of U.S. conventional forces and its over-reliance on atomic power.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] At the time of the Prague crisis, roughly ten ill-equipped and poorly trained U.S. and West European divisions faced over thirty Soviet divisions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] When taking into account Defense Department complaints that the U.S. atomic arsenal and the air power to use it were starkly inadequate, it became clear that the U.S. lacked a credible military deterrent in Europe.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The Czechoslovak coup changed the whole tone of the debate on the U.S. military budget.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] It helped spark a new round of Pentagon lobbying for a substantial rise in the military budget, while the NSC called for "a worldwide counter-offensive" against the Soviet bloc, including U.S. military aid to the Western European Union.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Truman responded to the crisis with a grim nationwide radio address on 17 March calling for a renewal of selective service, which had been allowed to lapse the previous year.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He also sought congressional approval for a programme of Universal Military Training (UMT).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He aimed to send a signal of determination to the Soviet Union that U.S. military posture was strong and that the country with this expansion of military preparedness was also prepared in the future to rearm massively if necessary.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Congress rejected UMT, but did vote to resume selective service, and voted the money for a seventy-group air force, 25% larger than the official request.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Nevertheless, the change in American foreign policy in response to the crisis-like atmosphere of early 1948 was more symbolic than real.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] American willingness to consult on new security arrangements for Europe was the product of neither a changed estimate of Soviet intentions nor a readiness to take on a larger share of the burden of defending Western Europe.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Rather, it was a tactical maneuver intended to mitigate the effect of the coup in Czechoslovakia and the brief but intense war scare that followed.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] As a result, a series of quick fixes followed to ensure that American forces would not be caught completely off guard in the event of war.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] More important was the sensitivity with which American officials now treated the nervousness of their European counterparts; the Americans now became more willing to take steps to boost morale in Europe and ease the now-widespread anxieties there.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The coup and the Berlin Blockade that June made clear that constant reassurance was needed to bind the Europeans to the U.S. system; hence, the remobilization of U.S. armed forces began.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Indeed, the fear of war between the Soviets and the West reached a high point after the coup.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Clay sent an alarming telegram from Berlin that advised of its likelihood: "Within the last few weeks, I have felt a subtle change in Soviet attitude which I cannot define but which now gives me a feeling that it may come with dramatic suddenness".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] General Omar Bradley later wrote that when he read Clay's "lugubrious assessment" in Washington he was "lifted right out of [his] chair", and George F.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Kennan wrote that the coup and the telegram had combined to create "a real war scare" where "the military and the intelligence fraternity" had "overreacted in the most deplorable way".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Only a week later, the Joint Chiefs of Staff recommended rearmament and a restoration of the draft.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In fact, Clay's warning had more to do with a request by Army director of intelligence Lt.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Stephen Chamberlain for material that would persuade Congress to spend more on military readiness than with any hard evidence of Soviet intent to launch a war in Europe.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Amidst the general alarm, more sanguine voices were also raised.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The Truman Administration had months earlier written off Czechoslovakia as little more than a Soviet satellite; in November 1947 U.S.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Marshall told a cabinet meeting that the Soviets would probably soon consolidate their hold on Eastern Europe by clamping down on Czechoslovakia as a "purely defensive move", and Kennan cabled from Manila that the Soviets seemed to be consolidating their defences, not preparing for aggression.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He later wrote that the Prague coup and the Berlin Blockade were "defensive reactions" to the Marshall Plan's initial successes and to the Western decision to press for an independent West German state.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] This view of the event sees Truman's reaction as him seizing on a necessary crisis to sell the Marshall Plan and the rearmament programme the Pentagon had long been pushing.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Marshall's own reaction was that "in so far as international affairs are concerned, a seizure of power by the Communist Party in Czechoslovakia would not materially alter...the situation which has existed in the last three years".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Hillenkoetter had also written to Truman that "the timing of the coup in Czechoslovakia was forced upon the Kremlin when the non-Communists took action endangering Communist control of the police.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] A Communist victory in the May elections would have been impossible without such control".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In Italy, elections were scheduled for 18 April and the Communist-dominated Popular Democratic Front stood a realistic chance of victory.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In the hysteria and foreboding that gripped Western circles following the Czech coup, it was concluded that similar tactics could be employed in Italy, whose citizens might not even have a chance to vote.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] British Foreign Minister Ernest Bevin and the British Cabinet saw the cooperation between the two leading parties of the Italian left in almost apocalyptic terms, believing that once the Italian Communist Party (PCI) won power it would marginalise any moderating influence from the socialists.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Bevin immediately concluded that the "forces of democratic Socialism" must be strengthened in Italy, and that Britain must support the Christian Democrats, despite all of their faults.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The Italian foreign minister, despite his alarm over the coup's timing, remained optimistic, assuring Bevin (who saw Italy as "the immediate danger spot") that the army and police were in excellent shape and that the coup would have an adverse effect, turning swing voters away from the socialists.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Kennan cabled to suggest the PCI should be outlawed and the U.S. should intervene militarily in the likely event of a civil war, but he quickly softened his line.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, the coup was one of several factors that led a strong plurality of voters to vote for Christian Democracy and defeat the left.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Stalin, satisfied that America had not moved militarily after the Czech coup and unwilling to provoke war, respected the result, considering Italy a Western country.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In France, interesting political currents were also set in motion.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The United States was still pushing the French government to support German rehabilitation.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In the aftermath of the coup, foreign minister Georges Bidault was afraid of stoking anti-German sentiment that the French Communist Party (PCF) could exploit and harness to instigate a coup of its own.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] At the same time, the coup had forced the hand of PCF leader Maurice Thorez, whose public remarks suggested that in the wake of a Soviet invasion, he would support the Red Army.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The Czech coup, the PCF's failed policy of sabotage and the Marshall Plan's likely passage were all beginning to sway French public opinion.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] 70% of French people now believed the U.S. would do more than any other country to help France, compared to 7% who thought the USSR would do more.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Despite French concern about Germany, it was becoming increasingly clear that the Soviet threat was greater than the German.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] France would still seek an advantageous power position vis-à-vis Germany, but it was becoming reconciled to the prospect of a rehabilitated Germany as part of postwar Europe.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Along with passage of the Marshall Plan, the other far-reaching implication of the Czech coup for U.S. foreign policy was to heed Bevin's call for a Western defence association.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 26 February, Bevin again reiterated that the best way to prevent another Czechoslovakia was to evolve a joint Western military strategy, and this time he got a more receptive hearing, especially considering American anxiety over Italy.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] That spring, European leaders quietly met with U.S. defence, military and diplomatic officials at the Pentagon, under Marshall's orders, exploring a framework for a new and unprecedented association for mutual defence.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The following year, NATO would ultimately be born out of these talks.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The **1953 Plzeň uprising** occurred when workers in the Czechoslovak city of Plzeň revolted in violent protest for three days, from 31 May to 2 June, against the currency reforms of state party, the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The estimated number of casualties is 200 injured, none fatally.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] After the communist party took over power in 1948 it started to concentrate production on heavy industry, especially in armament production.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The agricultural sector was forcibly collectivised.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] But these policies led to shortages of customer goods, especially food, accompanied by an inflation of 28 percent.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The government's reaction was to increase the prices of state-supplied goods at the start of 1953.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] This led to growing disaffection among people, and to short-lived strikes.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The next step to be implemented was a currency reform, which amounted to a devaluation of savings.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] All savings were devalued in the ratio of fifty to one, all salaries in the ratio of five to one – small groups of people were exempted.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] All obligations of the state were abolished.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] Rationing of food at subsidized prices was stopped and work quotas increased.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The reform was announced on 31 May at 22:00, after months of rumors and denials by state representatives.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] Plzeň is a city in western Bohemia with large concentration of heavy industry, the largest factory being the famous Škoda Works.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] In the previous years and decades, the city saw many strike actions by workers demanding improvement of their living standards.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] Many of the strikes were led by the Communist party itself.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] As long as the Party's reforms after 1948 favoured the workers in heavy industry, there was no reason to expect troubles.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] But in 1953 the factory management of Škoda Works deliberately paid off the wages for May one week earlier - thus reducing their values by 80% after the currency reform was announced.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] News of the reform spread quickly among night shift workers in a plant of the Škoda Works in Plzeň, who then went on strike.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The next day, in the morning, they decided to march to the city centre.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] Around noon the people attacked the city hall, and started to build barricades in the streets, and destroyed symbols of the communist party.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] Posters and slogans asking for the end of single party rule appeared.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] Some of the local communists and uniformed policemen had joined or were forced to join the rebellion, and 2,000 students had joined too.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] Nearby Bory prison was attacked with intention of releasing the prisoners, but the attack failed.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] No central leadership of the uprising was established; its actions were chaotic and uncoordinated.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] To suppress the uprising, strong reinforcements were called to the city, consisting of armed units of the Border Guard, the Czechoslovak People's Army, the People's Militia, the StB and the troops of the Ministry of National Security.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] During the afternoon, these units gradually regained control of the city, and in the evening there were only isolated skirmishes.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The government sent two police battalions totalling about 8,000 men, and an army unit of 2,500 men and 80 tanks to suppress the rebellion.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] During street fights about 220 rebels were injured.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] During the afternoon of 2 June, the last insurgents barricaded themselves in factories and gave up.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] Over 2,000 people were taken prisoner immediately and martial law was imposed.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The leaders of the uprising were promptly tried and sentenced to lengthy prison terms, one of whom was later executed.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] Communists and militiamen who had participated in the revolt were treated especially harshly.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] Strikes had started in 19 large industrial plants in Bohemia and Moravia, in industrial cities such as Kladno and Ostrava.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] These strikes didn't turn violent and ended within a week.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] An estimated 360,000 workers had gone on strike; up to 250,000 of them had demonstrated in the streets.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The leaders of the Communist party decided to present the event as having been provoked by agents of imperialism and this remained the official explanation until 1989.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The party was ordered to purge members suspected of "social-democratism" or of low levels of loyalty.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The army stated that any future uprising would be suppressed immediately.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] On 8 June the measures instituted on 31 May were recalled, except for the currency reform; also prices were reduced somewhat.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] This and other uprisings in Central Europe forced the leaders of the Soviet Union to exercise greater control over these countries.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] No further violent uprising occurred in Czechoslovakia until the Warsaw Pact invasion of 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The Velvet Revolution (1989) that ended the power of the communist party was mostly bloodless.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] Detailed knowledge of the 1953 events in Plzeň was and still is relatively low among the Czech public.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1953-plzeň-uprising] The shaken trust in the stability of the currency lasted for decades.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The first of several massive protests against the communist government of the Polish People's Republic took place in Poznań from 28 to 30 June 1956.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Demonstrations by workers demanding better working conditions began at Poznań's Cegielski Factories and were met with violent repression.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] A crowd of approximately 100,000 people gathered in the city centre near the local Ministry of Public Security building.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] About 400 tanks and 10,000 soldiers of the Polish People's Army and the Internal Security Corps under the command of the Polish-Soviet general Stanislav Poplavsky were ordered to suppress the demonstration and during the pacification fired at the protesting civilians.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The death toll is estimated from 57 to over a hundred people, including a 13-year-old boy, Romek Strzałkowski.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The Poznań protests were an important milestone on the way to the Polish October and the installation of a less Soviet-controlled government.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] After Joseph Stalin's death, the process of de-Stalinization prompted debates on fundamental issues throughout the entire Eastern Bloc.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Nikita Khrushchev's speech *On the Cult of Personality and Its Consequences* had wide implications both inside the Soviet Union and in other communist countries.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The death of Poland's hardline Communist leader Bolesław Bierut on 12 March 1956—allegedly from shock at the content of the Secret Speech—gave further fuel to the movement for change.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Anti-communist resistance in Poland was also bolstered, and a group of opposition leaders and cultural figures founded the Crooked Circle Club (Polish: *Klub Krzywego Koła*) in Warsaw.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] It promoted discussions about Polish independence, questioned the efficiency of the state controlled economy, and government disdain and even persecution of World War II veterans of Polish Armed Forces in the West and Armia Krajowa.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] While the intelligentsia expressed their dissatisfaction with discussions and publications (*bibuła*), workers took to the streets.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The living conditions in Poland did not improve, contrary to government propaganda, and workers increasingly found that they had little power compared to bureaucracy of the Party (*nomenklatura*).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The city of Poznań was one of the largest urban and industrial centers of the Polish People's Republic.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Tensions were growing there, particularly since autumn of 1955.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Workers in the largest factory in the city, the Joseph Stalin Metal Industries, were complaining about higher taxes for the most productive workers (*udarnik*), which affected several thousands of workers.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Local directors were unable to make any significant decisions due to micromanagement by the higher officials; over several months, petitions, letters and delegations were sent to the Polish Ministry of Machine Industry and the Central Committee of Polish United Workers' Party, to no avail.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Finally, a delegation of about 27 workers was sent to Warsaw around 23 June.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] On the night of 26 June, the delegation returned to Poznań, confident that some of their demands had been considered in a favourable light.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] However, the next morning, the Minister of Machine Industry met with the workers and withdrew several promises that their delegation had been given in Warsaw.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] On 28 June 1956, a spontaneous strike started at 6:30 a.m. at the multifactory complex of the Joseph Stalin Metal Industries (ZiSPO).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Around 80% of its workers, most of whom had lost bonus pay in June as the government suddenly raised the required work quota, took to the streets demanding pay compensation and some concessions of freedom, marching towards the city centre.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Workers at other plants, as well as institutions and students, joined the procession.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Between 9 and 11 a.m., about 100,000 people gathered on the Adam Mickiewicz Square in front of the Imperial Castle in Poznań, surrounded by buildings occupied by the city and Party authorities and police headquarters.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The demonstrators demanded lower food prices, wage increases and the revocation of some recent changes in the law that had eroded workers' conditions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] They further requested a visit from Polish Prime Minister Józef Cyrankiewicz, as the local government declared that they had no authority to solve the workers' problems.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Some police officers also joined the crowd.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] After 10 a.m., the situation rapidly deteriorated, with rumours spreading that members of the negotiating delegation had been arrested.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] At 11:30 am, the arms depot at the prison building was seized and the firearms distributed among the demonstrators.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The crowd ransacked the Communist Party's local headquarters and then, at around 11 a.m., attacked the office of the Ministry of Public Security on Kochanowskiego Street, but were repulsed when the first shots were fired from its windows into the crowd.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] From then until 6:00 pm, they seized or besieged many government buildings and institutions in and around Poznań, including the district courthouse and the prosecutor's office, the radio jamming station on Dąbrowskiego Street, and police stations in Junikowo, Wilda, Swarzędz, Puszczykowo and Mosina.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The prison camp in Mrowino and the military school at the Poznań University of Technology were seized and weapons taken.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The police documents at the local police station, procuratorate and courthouse were destroyed.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] In the meantime, at about 11:00 am, 16 tanks, 2 armored personnel carriers and 30 other vehicles were sent from the Officers' School of Armored and Mechanized Formations, a Poznań garrison, to protect the designated buildings, but no shots were exchanged between them and the insurgents.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] These soldiers engaged in friendly conversation with the protesters; some reports state that two tanks were seized and some troops disarmed.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Konstantin Rokossovsky, the Soviet general, and Poland's Defence Minister, then decided to take personal control, and the situation changed dramatically.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The Russian officers arrived at 2 p.m. at Ławica Airport and took command.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Poplavsky did not bother to use local regulars from Poznań garrisons, instead taking other troops from Silesian Military District and recalling special troops from the Biedrusko military base north of Poznań.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The troops were told that the protesters were led and organized by "German provocateurs", who were attempting to darken Poland's image during the ongoing Poznań International Fair.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Between 4 p.m. and 5 a.m. the following day, troops from the Polish 10th Armored Division, Polish 19th Armored Division, Polish 4th Infantry Division and Polish 5th Infantry Division, totaling 10,300, and the Internal Security Corps, under the command of Poplavsky, entered Poznań.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] A two-hour long procession of tanks, armored cars, field guns, and lorries full of troops went through the city and surrounded it.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The detainees were taken to Ławica Airport, where they were subjected to brutal interrogation; 746 persons were detained until 8 August.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The protests continued until 30 June, when the troops finally pacified the city, after exchanging fire with some of the more violent demonstrators.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] There are varying estimates of casualties.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Estimates of a similar range, such as the "over 70 deaths", can be found in media reports.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] About 250 people were arrested in the first few days, including 196 workers; several hundred others were arrested in the following weeks.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Stanisław Hejmowski, Michał Grzegorzewicz and Gerard Kujanek (among others), the lawyers who defended them, faced repressions by the government for their statements that the government's actions had led to the death of innocent civilians.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The government failed in its attempts to coerce the detainees into stating that they were provoked by foreign (Western) secret services; nonetheless, this became the official line of the government for years to come.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Soon the ideologues realized that they had lost the support of the Soviet Union, and the regime turned to conciliation by announced wage rises and other reforms.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Realizing the need for a change in leadership, the Polish communists chose a new leader, Władysław Gomułka, who was considered a moderate; this transition is known as Polish October (or "Gomułka Thaw").
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] In spite of this, the communist authorities censored all information on the Poznań events for a quarter of a century.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Historians were denied source materials for research, and censorship was effective in eliminating any mention of the events of June 1956 from publicly available sources.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Persecution of the most active participants would be carried out for many years.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The memory of the events was preserved by the participants and members of opposition.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] After the Gdańsk Agreement in 1980, the Solidarity movement, as one of its first actions decided to raise a monument in memory of the Poznań June 1956 events.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Many historians consider the Poznań 1956 protests to be an important milestone in modern history of Poland, and one of the events that precipitated the fall of communism in Poland.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] Nonetheless, the protests of 1956 were not motivated by clearly anti-communist ideology; the workers' demands were mostly of an economic nature, centering around better work conditions rather than any other clearly articulated political objectives.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] The workers sang "The Internationale" and their banners read "We demand bread." It was the government's consistent failure to fulfil the first demand which eventually led to the demands for political change, but even during the history of Solidarity few demanded wide political reforms.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] On 23 June 1996, the Children of June of '56 was unveiled in Poznań.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] It stands in dedication to the children who participated in the protests.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1956-poznań-protests] On 21 June 2006, to commemorate the 50th anniversary of the events, the Polish parliament Sejm declared 28 June to be a national holiday in Poland; the *Day of Remembrance of the Poznań June 1956*.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The **1965 Soviet economic reform**, sometimes called the **Kosygin reform** (Russian: Косыгинская реформа) or **Liberman reform**, named after E.G.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Liberman, was a set of planned changes in the economy of the USSR.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] A centerpiece of these changes was the introduction of profitability and sales as the two key indicators of enterprise success.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Some of an enterprise's profits would go to three funds, used to reward workers and expand operations; most would go to the central budget.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The reforms were introduced politically by Alexei Kosygin—who had just become Premier of the Soviet Union following the removal of Nikita Khrushchev—and ratified by the Central Committee in September 1965.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] They reflected some long-simmering wishes of the USSR's mathematically-oriented economic planners, and initiated the shift towards increased decentralization in the process of economic planning.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The reforms, coinciding with the Eighth Five-Year Plan, led to continued growth of the Soviet economy.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The success of said reforms was short-lived, and with the events of Prague in 1968, fueled by Moscow's implementation of the reforms in Eastern Bloc countries, led to the reforms being curtailed.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Economists like Lev Gatovsky and Liberman were instrumental in framing the theoretical underpinnings of the Soviet economic reforms of the 1960s, advocating for the use of profit motives and market mechanisms within a socialist framework.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Under Lenin, the New Economic Policy had allowed and used the concepts of profit and incentives for regulation of the Soviet economy.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Stalin transformed this policy rapidly with the collectivization of farms and nationalization of industry, which was the result of the acceleration of central planning as exemplified by the "Five-Year Plans".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Since about 1930, the Soviet Union had used a centralized system to manage its economy.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In this system, a single bureaucracy created economic plans, which assigned workers to jobs, set wages, dictated resource allocation, established the levels of trade with other countries, and planned the course of technological progress.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Retail prices for consumer goods were fixed at levels intended for market clearing.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The prices of wholesale goods were fixed, also, but these served an accounting function more than a market mechanism.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Collective farms also paid centrally determined prices for the supplies they needed, and unlike other sectors their workers received wages directly dependent on the profitability of the operation.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Although Soviet enterprises were theoretically governed by the principle of *khozraschet* (Russian: хозрасчёт, lit.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] 'business bookkeeping', or "accounting")—which required them to meet planners' expectations within the system of set prices for their inputs and outputs—they had little control over the biggest decisions affecting their operations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Managers did have a responsibility to plan future gross output, which they chronically underestimated in order to later exceed the prediction.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The managers then received bonuses (*premia*) for surplus product regardless of whether it was produced in a cost-effective manner or whether their enterprise was profitable overall.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The bonuses for output came in amounts sometimes equal to the managers' base salaries.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The system also incentivized pointless increases in the size, weight, and cost of production outputs, simply because "more" had been produced.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The economic reforms emerged during a period of great ideological debate over economic planning.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] More mathematical, "cybernetic", viewpoints were at first considered deviant from orthodox Marxist economics, which considered the value of goods to derive strictly from labor.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] This doctrine, elaborated in such works as Stalin's 1952 book, *Economic Problems of Socialism in the USSR*, described the price system as a capitalist relic which would eventually disappear from communist society.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Nevertheless, computerized economics gained an important role for top planners, even while conventional Marxist–Leninist political economy was taught in most schools and promoted for public consumption.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The rising influence of statistical planning in the Soviet economy was reflected in the creation of the Central Economic Mathematical Institute (Центральный экономико-математический институт; TSEMI), led by Vasily Sergeevich Nemchinov.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Nemchinov, along with linear programming inventor Leonid Kantorovich and investment analyst Viktor Valentinovich Novozhilov, received the Lenin Prize in 1965.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The battle between "optimal" planning and convention planning raged throughout the 1960s.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Another tendency in economic planning emphasized "normative value of processing", or the importance of needs and wants in evaluating the value of production.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Major changes throughout the Soviet world became possible in 1964 with the ousting of Nikita Khrushchev and the rise of Alexei Kosygin and Leonid Brezhnev.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Economic policy was a significant area of retrospective anti-Khrushchev criticism in the Soviet press.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] This 'reformist' economic tendency in the Soviet Union had corollaries and some mutual reinforcement in Eastern Europe.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Kosygin criticized the inefficiency and inertia of economic policy under the previous administration.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] He presented a plan, including the ideas expressed by Liberman and Nemchinov, to the Communist Party Central Committee Plenum in September 1965.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The Central Committee's acceptance of the plan became crucial for practical implementation of theoretical ideas.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] According to official rationale for the reform, the increasing complexity of economic relations reduced the efficacy of economic planning and therefore reduced economic growth.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] It was recognized that the existing system of planning did not motivate enterprises to reach high rates of production or to introduce organizational or technical innovations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Given more freedom to deviate publicly from party orthodoxy, newspapers offered new proposals for the Soviet economy.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Antonov published an article in *Izvestia* on November 22, 1961, with the title "For All and For Oneself"—advocating more power for enterprise directors.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] A widely publicized economic rationale for reform came from Evsei Liberman of the Kharkov Institute of Engineering and Economics.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] An article by Liberman on this topic, titled "Plans, Profits, and Bonuses" appeared in *Pravda* in September 1962.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Liberman, influenced by the economic "optimizers", argued for the (re)introduction of profitability as a core economic indicator.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These proposals were controversial, and criticized especially as regressions towards a capitalist economic system.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Critics also argued that reliance on profitability would skew the proportions in which different goods were produced.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Unlike Liberman in 1962, Trapeznikov suggested that the need for reform had been embraced by party decisionmakers and would soon become a reality.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In the following month, *Pravda* published six more articles from academicians, planners, and managers advocating reform.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Several economic experiments were initiated to test Liberman's proposals.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These began in 1964 with new policies for two garment factories: the Bolshevichka in Moscow and the Mayak in Gorky.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] When operations at the garment factories proved tolerably successful, the experiment was expanded to about 400 other enterprises, mostly in large cities.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] One experiment in Lviv involved a coal mine and factories producing clothing, shoes, and heavy lifting equipment.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The coal mine, in particular, reportedly became more profitable after shifting to a system using bonuses and more independent decisionmaking.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Some of the experimental plants ran into problems, however, due to the unreliability of suppliers continuing to operate on the old system.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The Mayak plant faced a dilemma in trying to implement the centrally mandated experimental reforms, while simultaneously receiving contradictory orders from the local *sovnarkhoz* (regional council).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The reform was administered by the Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union and the Council of Ministers.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The number of policy targets was reduced from 30 to 9 (the rest remained indicators).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Enterprises were required to determine the detailed range and variety of products, using their own funds to invest in production, establish long-term contractual arrangements with suppliers and customers and to determine the number of personnel.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Key importance was attributed to the integral indicators of economic efficiency of production — profits and profitability.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] There was the opportunity to create a number of funds based on the expense of profits — funds for the development of production, material incentives, housing, etc.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The enterprise was allowed to use the funds at its discretion.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Pricing: Wholesale sales prices would be recalibrated to reflect costs and encourage economic efficiency.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The most important changes resulting from the Liberman/Kosygin reforms involved the role of profit in the Soviet economic system.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] *Rentabelnost'* ("profitability", Russian: рентабельность) and *realizatsiya* ("sales", Russian: реализация) became the twin success indicators for enterprises.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] *Rentabelnost'* was defined in terms of the *ratio* between profits and capital, while *realizatsiya* (also meaning "implementation") depended on the total volume of sales.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Success by these measurements led to the allocation of money to a fund, which could be disbursed according to a pre-defined sequence.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The funds first went to pay for capital—including interest paid to *Gosbank*, the State Bank.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Then, they went to the new incentive funds.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Finally, they could be used by an enterprise to expand its capital for operations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Any profit extending above the maximum for spending would go to the central budget.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The production development fund (PDF): A 'development' fund for the overall organization.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Formerly, bonuses had come from the same fund as wages.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Now, enterprise managers had slightly more discretion over how to allocate them.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] They could move some amounts of money between the bonus fund and the social welfare fund.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] They also had more power to influence wages by classifying different workers.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In practice, the bonuses had the greatest impact on the payment of elite personnel (technicians and "employees" as opposed to "workers"), thereby counteracting the effect of Khrushchev-era wage reforms.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] An experimental system introduced at some enterprises offered extra bonuses for specific achievements—not just as a portion of total profits.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] For example, engineers using fuel more efficiently (during a shortage) could receive large premia calculated as a percentage of the money they saved.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Along with more direct responsibility for the wage fund, enterprises also gained the power to fire workers.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In fact, the reform gave new incentive for layoffs, which in some cases could increase profitability.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] (When these occurred, the workers did not have a 'social safety net' in place in the form of unemployment insurance and career assistance).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] To encourage accurate planning, enterprises now would be punished for performing below *or above* their planned goals.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Enterprises would also pay rent for land and natural resources.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The rationale for this practice was economic optimization.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] For example, land of differing quality required different inputs of manpower to achieve the same outputs, and thus should factor differently into the budget of an enterprise.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Bank loans, to be repaid later with interest, would be used to fund more investment projects—to incentive the careful use of funds and the speedy creation of profit.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Five different interest rates would be set, ranging from preferential to normal to punitive.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] An additional capital charge—i.e., tax—would be assessed for each enterprise based on the capital it retained: working capital, equipment, and surplus stocks.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Enterprises were to submit annual plans, called *tekhpromfinplans (from Russian: техпромфинплан (ru:Техпрофинплан) - technical and financial production plan)*, stipulating production plans by quarter and month.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Higher-ups would then approve these plans (or not) and allocate supplies and money.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The enterprise then sells its products, within the constraints of the plan.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] It is empowered to reject or return (within ten days) unneeded inputs to the supplier.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The key change which represented "decentralization" was the delegation of responsibility over modernization investments.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] However, modernization plans remained subject to central approval, as well as approval from the bank which lent the money.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The amount of development expected under these auspices fell far short of expectations, as the necessary labour and materials were simply undersupplied.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] One response to this problem in 1969 was to shift more incentives to the contractors.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] For the "optimal planners" this limited decentralization was inadequate, and the new importance assigned to "profit" was incomplete because enterprises did not control enough of the factors which might affect it.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These councils spelled the end of a short-lived phase of worker control over production, which the Bolsheviks regarded as inefficient.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Under the New Economic Policy beginning in 1921, enterprises were classified based on their relative interdependence (and necessity to war production) or autonomy (i.e. those "endowed with complete financial and commercial independence").
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The many enterprises in the latter category were not nationalized, but instead placed under the guidance of the VSNKh, with the plan to group them into "trusts" based on production chains or geographic proximity.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] This model underwent various reorganizations, including the strengthening of *edinonachalie*, control of production units by a single manager.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These single managers at times controlled a wide range of production activities within a single area.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The economic reform of 1957 reintroduced the *sovnarkhozy*, 104 in number, to govern production by region.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Where applicable, these corresponded closely with the boundaries of the *oblasty* (political jurisdictions).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Complaints immediately arose that these councils did not optimize overall production chains, due to their regional focus, and that they conflicted with the authority of *Gosplan*.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In 1962, the 104 *sovnarkhozy* were consolidated into 47 larger jurisdictions (one of which controlled all of Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, Tadzhikistan, and Kirgizia).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] However, by 1962–1963, the *sovnarkhozy* were becoming subordinate to numerous other agencies and organizations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Gosplan was to be stripped of its planning authority in favor of a revitalized VSNKh.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Kosygin took aim at these "outdated forms of management" and included in his 1965 speech a return to ministries as core administrators.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] His plan resembled the ministry system under Stalin, but with a smaller number: nine all-Union ministries organized by industry (e.g., Ministry of Light Industry, Ministry of the Radio Industry, Ministry of the Chemical Industry) and eleven supervising operations within each union-republic.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The latter regional agencies reported both to the local council and to the central ministry with jurisdiction over their production type.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Gosplan had the responsibility for creating annual and long-term plans, and for guiding development and resource management.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] *Gossnab* became the primary coordinator of material-technical supply, and was charged with large-scale analysis (possibly using computers) to increase supply chain efficiency.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The 1965 reforms somewhat altered the role of the Party in economic administration.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Local officials were to oversee operations from a distance to ensure compliance with the spirit of the reforms.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The plan called for more detailed and scientific central planning, including annual targets.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These plans would be calculated using computer systems.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Distribution of supplies and products would take place in different ways.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Central planners would allocate certain scarce and vital goods.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] For others, enterprises could form "direct ties" within which they developed a contractual exchange relationship.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The authors of the reforms knew from the outset that changes would take effect gradually, based on the careful writing of plans through the years 1966 and 1967.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The first 43 enterprises, along with several "experiments" for which planning began before the September 1965 Plenum, shifted to the new model at the beginning of 1966.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Transfer of another 180–200 was accomplished in early 1966.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These were already profitable, well-positioned businesses, and reflected well on the reform in early evaluations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] On July 1, 1966, 430 more enterprises were transferred; these included some large operations and themselves constituted 12% of total production.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] By the end of 1966, more than 704 enterprises had switched.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The Eighth Five-Year Plan would have instantiated some of the proposed reforms.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] (The Five-Year Plan dealt with a broad range of issues, with more of a focus on people's overall living conditions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Most light industry was to transfer at the beginning of 1967.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The remaining enterprises to switch over in two stages, taking effect on July 1, 1967, and January 1, 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The complete transfer of all enterprises proceeded steadily, if not exactly on schedule.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] By April 1, 1967, 2,500 enterprises, responsible for 20% of output, had switched.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] By the end of the year, 7,000 industrial enterprises (out of 45,000), 1,500 trucking firms (out of 4,100), and all 25 railroad systems had transferred.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Together these made up the backbone of Soviet industry.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] They were followed by smaller enterprises: 11,000 more in 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The plan met with considerable initial confusion from enterprise managers who, throughout their careers, had underestimated their potential output in order to later exceed their quota.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Also difficult was the requirement to comply with the new directives before all aspects of the economy (i.e., prices, resource availability) had shifted over.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] And the reluctance of certain bureaucrats to comply with the new policies was the subject of sustained criticism in the press, including multiple editorials by Liberman himself.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In April 1966, for example, Liberman recommended creating a "brain trust of the reconstruction" which could veto counter-reformist policies in the bureaucracy.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Officials at the higher administrative levels (i.e., the ministries), continued to issue orders at odds with the profitability plans of the enterprise managers.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Some traditional problems—such as accumulation (which undercut profitability) of surplus valuable supplies, lest they be needed later in a time of shortage—persisted.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Gossnab and the ministries were blamed for failing to make the appropriate inputs available to the enterprises.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] A price revision, the first since 1955, was announced in mid-1966, apparently following some non-trivial internal disputes.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The revision called for moderate re-alignment of prices, to conform more with production costs, and went into effect in July 1967.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Wholesale fuel and ore prices increased substantially.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Prices on consumer goods did not officially increase at all; yet consumers paid higher prices for things they wanted and needed, since newer, more expensive goods were introduced to the market, and the old versions withdrawn.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Many enterprises were encouraged to sell or give away excess equipment, since all available capital was factored into the calculation of productivity.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Certain measurements of efficiency improved.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These included rising sales per rouble worth of capital and falling wages per rouble of sales.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The enterprises rendered large portions of their profits, sometimes 80%, to the central budget.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These payments of "free" remaining profits substantially exceeded capital charges.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] However, central planners were not satisfied with the impact of the reform.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In particular, they observed that wages had increased without a commensurate rise in productivity.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Many of the specific changes were revised or reversed in 1969–1971.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The reforms somewhat reduced the role of the Party in micromanaging economic operations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The backlash against economic reformism joined with opposition to political liberalization to trigger the full-blown invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Soviet officials and press nevertheless continued to advance the idea of the 1965 reform.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] A series of protests against the United States' involvement in the Vietnam War took place prior to and during the 1968 Democratic National Convention in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The protests lasted approximately seven days, from August 23 to August 29, 1968, and drew an estimated 7,000 to 10,000 anti-war protesters in total.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Chicago authorities attempted to prevent the protests from occurring but were unsuccessful, and the city promised "law and order" to suppress the protesters.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Despite the small size of the protests, many demonstrators, reporters, and bystanders were met with unprecedented levels of police brutality and violence by the Chicago Police Department, particularly in Grant Park and Michigan Avenue during the convention.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The actions by Chicago police, the Illinois National Guard, and other law enforcement agencies were later described by the National Commission on the Causes and Prevention of Violence as a "police riot".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] During the evening of August 28, 1968, with the police riot occurring on Michigan Avenue in front of the Democratic Party's convention headquarters and the Conrad Hilton hotel, television networks broadcast live as the anti-war protesters began the now-iconic chant: "The whole world is watching".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Following the March on the Pentagon in October 1967 which drew 100,000 protesters, David Dellinger's National Mobilization Committee to End the War in Vietnam (often referred to as "MOBE") proposed a massive anti-war demonstration to coincide with the 1968 Democratic National Convention.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In early 1968, the National Mobilization Committee opened a Chicago office directed by Rennie Davis and Tom Hayden, who were leading political organizers at the time and former leaders of Students for a Democratic Society.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] MOBE was an umbrella organization that included groups who were opposed to American participation in the Vietnam War.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] MOBE was run by a small executive board that set up a general framework for mass demonstrations, sent out invitations to the over 500 groups on its mailing lists, and coordinated activities between the groups.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] MOBE recognized and supported all tactics from marching to civil disobedience.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] MOBE's main aim was to get the largest turnouts at its functions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] David Dellinger, MOBE chairman, believed that "the tendency to intensify militancy without organizing wide political support [was] self-defeating.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] For Chicago, MOBE originally planned for two large-scale marches and an end-of-convention rally at Soldier Field.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The goal was originally a massive show of force outside the International Amphitheatre.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] MOBE also planned to have workshops and movement centers distributed in 10 parks throughout the city, many in predominantly black areas, to allow demonstrators and participating groups to follow their particular focuses.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The Youth International Party was one of the major groups in the organization of the protests.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Abbie Hoffman, Jerry Rubin, and a few friends engaged in conversation at Hoffman's apartment on New Year's Eve, 1967.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] They discussed the events of the year, such as the Summer of Love and the Pentagon demonstration.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The idea of having a free music festival in Chicago was suggested to defuse political tension.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Over the next week, the Youth International Party took shape.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Its members, known as "Yippies" politicized hippie ideology and used street theater and other tactics to critique the culture of the United States and induce change.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In preparation for the Chicago convention, the Yippies held the "Yip-In", and the "Yip-Out" at Grand Central Station in New York City.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Both events were planned simply as Human Be-In, with live music.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The event was used to promote peace, love and harmony, and as a trial run for Chicago.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The black banner of an anarchist group was hung on the wall, bearing the words, "Up Against the Wall Mother Fucker" in red.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] As the "Yip-In" progressed, relations between the police and Yippies became strained.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Two people climbed a large clock and removed the hands; the police responded by clearing the station.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] They formed a skirmish line, ordered the people to disperse, and then started forcing their way through the crowd.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The "Yip-Out" was similar in purpose but held in Central Park.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] To obtain the permits and aid from New York City officials necessary for the event, Yippies performed a sit-in at the mayor's office until the Mayor would negotiate on permits.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In the end, an agreement was made on staging, electricity, police presence, bathrooms, and other necessities for running a music festival.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Police milled in the crowd giving considerable leeway to the proceedings which led to a peaceable day.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The Yippies took a radical approach to the Democratic National Convention.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] They wrote articles, published fliers, made speeches and held rallies and demonstrations, to announce that they were coming to Chicago.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Threats were made that nails would be thrown from overpasses to block roads; cars would be used to block intersections, main streets, police stations and National Guard armories; LSD would be dumped in the city's water supply and the convention would be stormed.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] However, none of these threats came to fruition.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Nonetheless, city officials in Chicago prepared for all possible threats.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] A vilification campaign led by Chicago authorities worked in favor of the Yippies' plan.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] One of the Yippies' main tactics was to use street theatre to create an experience that drew the attention of mainstream America.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Yippie activities were used to put across the message that the average American didn't have control over the political process.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] On a Wednesday night, networks moved their coverage away from the Amphitheater where the delegates were voting on the nomination, to a "pitched battle" in front of the Conrad Hilton hotel.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In the buildup to the convention and amid tensions following the 1968 Chicago riots, Mayor Richard J.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Daley repeatedly denounced the various anti–Vietnam War protest groups mobilizing for demonstrations and declared, “Law and order will be maintained.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Chicago's security forces prepared for the protests during the convention.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Besides the standard gun and billy club, Chicago Police Department officers had mace and riot helmets.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] For the convention, the CPD borrowed a new portable communications system from the military, thus increasing communication between field officers and command posts.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] All summer long, police officers had received refresher training on crowd control and riot techniques.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] During the convention itself, Police Academy instructors were with the reserve forces, giving last-minute reminders.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Mayor Daley, citing intelligence reports of potential violence, put the 12,000 members of the Chicago Police Department on twelve-hour shifts, while the U.S.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Army placed 6,000 troops in position to protect the city during the convention and nearly 6,000 members of the National Guard were sent to the city, with an additional 5,000 National Guard on alert, bolstered by up to 1,000 FBI and military intelligence officers, and 1,000 Secret Service agents.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] To satisfy manpower requirements, the City put the force on 12-hour shifts, instead of the normal 8-hour shifts.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] This gave police commanders approximately 50% more field officers to deal with disturbances.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Two-thirds of the officers would continue with the normal police duties with the remaining third available for special assignment.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In the Amphitheatre, the City concentrated 500 officers filling various roles.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In Lincoln Park, the number of officers patrolling during the daytime was doubled, but the majority of the officers assigned to the Lincoln Park area were held in reserve, ready to respond to any disturbance.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In suspected trouble areas, police patrols were heavy.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Further away from the center patrols were less frequent.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] This allowed the police to shift easily and quickly to control a problem without leaving an area unguarded.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] While maintaining a public image of total enforcement of all city, state, and federal laws, the Narcotics division was quietly reassigned to regular fieldwork, curtailing anti-drug operations during the DNC.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Police officials and Mayor Daley had worked with the National Guard to create a plan to use the Guard effectively.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] It would be called up at the beginning of the convention, but held in reserve at strategically placed armories or collection points such as Soldier Field.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] With the Guard in place at their armories, the CPD could request and receive assistance quickly.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Both MOBE and Yippie needed permits from the city to hold their respective events.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The city had several reasons for denying permits to MOBE and Yippie and thus stalled issuing permits.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The city was worried about a black rebellion, independent of the white protesters, during the convention.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] To avoid trouble, the City used its influence with black community organizations such as The Woodlawn Organization, the Black Consortium, and Operation Breadbasket to try to keep their constituents calm and peaceful.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Some of the militant black leaders were encouraged to leave town during the convention to avoid being implicated in any violence.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The city also believed that having large numbers of white protesters marching through the black ghettos with a heavy police or National Guard escort would inflame the ghettos and set off rioting.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Therefore, the City categorically denied any permit that included parks in or march routes through black areas.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Another argument the City used to deny permits was that the permits asked the city to set aside local and state ordinances.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] A city ordinance closed the city parks at 11 p.m., although this was not strictly enforced.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In a letter to Yippie, Deputy Mayor David Stahl gave eight rules for Yippie to follow, including submitting detailed plans and requirements, following all city, state, and federal ordinances, and toning down the rhetoric.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The Yippies refused, so the City felt justified in denying Yippie their permits.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In a last-ditch effort, MOBE filed a lawsuit in federal court seeking it to force Chicago to issue permits for a rally in Soldier Field or Grant Park.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Judge Lynch, Daley's former law partner, heard the case, and summarily dismissed the request, citing that the city could deny permits on the basis of protecting "public comfort, convenience, and welfare".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Although Chicago authorities and the media had anticipated 100,000 anti-war protesters to converge on Chicago during the week of the 1968 Democratic National Convention, an estimated 9,000 to 10,000 protesters arrived in the city on August 22–23 to participate in the demonstrations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] As the demonstrators arrived in the city, 23,000 police and National Guardsmen assembled in response.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The week's violence began with the shooting of Dean Johnson by Chicago police officers.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Dean Johnson, age 17, and another boy were stopped on the sidewalk by the officers for a curfew violation early on the morning of Thursday, August 22.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] When Johnson drew and fired a pistol at police (the gun misfired), police officers returned fire, hitting Johnson three times.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The Yippies and SDS hastily organized a memorial service for Johnson, but as one observer noted, due to poor planning "it turned out that no one had made any plans to actually do anything.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] We just milled around and began to fill up the intersection.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Two squad cars pulled up and the cops got out and told us to keep moving ... but they were pretty gentle about it".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] On Friday, August 23, Jerry Rubin and 50 Yippies attempted to formally nominate the Yippie candidate for president, Pigasus, a 150-pound pig that they had transported to the Civic Center plaza in an old station wagon.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] By the time Rubin arrived with Pigasus, 200 spectators had gathered on the Civic Center plaza.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Police officers were waiting, and after the pig was released, Rubin, folk singer Phil Ochs, and five other Yippies were arrested.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The remaining Yippies proceeded to the police headquarters at 11th and State streets to protest the arrests.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] At 6 a.m. on Saturday, August 24, continuous surveillance began in Lincoln Park.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] On previous nights, the police had cleared Lincoln Park at 11 p.m. and maintained a significant presence during the day.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Women Strike for Peace attempted to hold a women-only picket at the Hilton Hotel, the main delegate hotel.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Despite plans for buses from around the country to bring hundreds of picketers, only 60 or so women showed up.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] At 10:30 p.m., the Yippies had built a bonfire near the southern area of Lincoln Park, and armed police soon confronted them.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] As protesters generally agreed not to attempt to stay in Lincoln Park after the curfew but to take the protest to the streets, poet Allen Ginsberg led 250 protesters out of the park at 11 p.m. and towards North Avenue.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] While 75 policemen and 4 police cars barred any reentrance to Lincoln Park, SDS leaders organized several hundred protesters to march through the streets chanting things such as "Peace Now".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] When the crowd stopped at Wells and North Avenue, blocking the intersection, a police contingent arrived and cleared the crowd.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Eleven people were arrested on charges of disorderly conduct, and several police vehicles were stoned before the crowd dispersed into the normal Saturday nightlife.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] On Sunday, MOBE had scheduled a 'Meet the Delegates' march and picket.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] At 2 p.m. there were between 200 and 300 picketers marching across the street from the Conrad Hilton, and another 500 marching south through the Loop chanting, "Hey, Hey LBJ, how many kids did you kill today".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] After the police arrival, those who were picketing moved into nearby Grant Park to avoid a mass arrest situation.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Once the marchers had reached Grant Park, there was a brief rally where Davis and Hayden claimed the day a success and then went to Lincoln Park where the Festival of Life music festival was beginning.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] At 4 p.m., the Festival started with proto-punk band MC5, the only band who showed up for the festival.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The police did not allow a flatbed truck to be brought in as a stage, fearing Yippies would use it to incite the crowd.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] When the concession stand owner insisted that Yippie stop using his electrical outlets to run the amplification equipment, confusion ensued.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] While Rubin and other Yippies tried to make frantic deals to get the sound back on, Hoffman used the confusion to try to bring in the flatbed truck.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] A deal was struck allowing the truck to be parked nearby, but not in, the park.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The crowd gathered around and on the truck did not realize an agreement had been reached and thought the truck was being sent away.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The crowd surged around the truck, pinning in the police officers.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Hoffman declared that the police had stopped the music festival, and proceeded to conduct a workshop on dispersal tactics to avoid arrest by police.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] As the next police shift came on duty, they were informed of the tense situation in the park.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Due to the number, frequency, diverseness, and exposure of the threats made by the protesters, the police were concerned about facing protesters armed with unknown weapons and unknown intentions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] At 9 p.m., police formed a skirmish line around the park bathrooms.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] This drew a crowd of spectators who heckled the police.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The crowd rapidly grew until the police charged into the crowd swinging their batons, scattering the crowd.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] At 11 p.m., the police pushed the protesters out of the park.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Most protesters left the park and congregated nearby, taunting the police.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Initially, when the police reached the edge of the park, they maintained their skirmish line.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] However, when a squad was ordered to 'clear' Clark Street to keep traffic flowing, the police lost control.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Yippie Jerry Rubin told a friend, "This is fantastic and it's only Sunday night.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] They might declare martial law in this town." Protesters, journalists, photographers, and bystanders were clubbed and beaten by the police.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Order was not restored in Old Town until early Monday morning.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] On Monday, August 26, demonstrators climbed on the *General John Logan Memorial* statue, leading to violent skirmishes with police in Grant Park.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Police hauled a young man down and arrested him, breaking his arm in the process.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Protestors chanted “kill the pigs” as the skirmishes with police unfolded.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In the early morning hours of August 28, 5,000 protesters had congregated in front of the Conrad Hilton hotel, which served as the convention headquarters, and across the street in Grant Park.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] At 2:15 a.m., Mayor Daley ordered 800 national guardsmen of the 33rd military police battalion to confront them.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The national guardsmen had been billeted at Soldier Field and in the armory building awaiting these very instructions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Donning battle gear, the guardsmen proceeded to Michigan Avenue and positioned themselves between the Conrad Hilton hotel and the protesters in Grant Park.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] While this stand-off occurred at Grant Park, 200 Chicago policemen used tear gas and dump trucks as improvised tanks to disperse protesters at Lincoln Park.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Among these protesters were 50 members of the Black Panthers.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] By this time, protesters were joined on 28 August by the Poor People's Campaign, now led by the Southern Christian Leadership Conference's Ralph Abernathy.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] This group had a permit and was split off from other demonstrators before being allowed to proceed to the amphitheater.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] When protesters at Grant Park eventually attempted to cross Michigan Avenue and storm the Conrad Hilton hotel, a 17-minute melee ensued, later known as "The Battle of Michigan Avenue." Reporters broadcast footage of the melee on television, along with footage from the floor of the convention.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Reporters estimated the crowd at 9,000 anti-war demonstrators, while police estimated 7,000 persons.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The police violence extended to encompass protesters, bystanders, reporters and photographers, while tear gas reached Hubert Humphrey in his hotel suite.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Police pushed protesters through plate-glass windows, then pursued them inside and beat them as they sprawled on the broken glass.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] 100 protesters and 119 police officers were treated for injuries, and 600 protesters were arrested.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Television cameras recorded the police brutality while demonstrators chanted "The whole world is watching".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] At the convention, several Democratic delegates made statements against Mayor Daley and the CPD, such as Senator Abraham Ribicoff who, speaking from the podium, denounced the use of "Gestapo tactics on the streets of Chicago" in his speech nominating George McGovern.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The hard line taken by the city was also seen on the convention floor itself.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In 1968, Terry Southern described the convention hall as "exactly like approaching a military installation; barbed-wire, checkpoints, the whole bit".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Inside the convention, journalists such as Mike Wallace and Dan Rather were roughed up by security; both these events were broadcast live on television.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Humphrey won the presidential nomination that night.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Paul Cowan of *The Village Voice* reports that after a speech by Eugene McCarthy in Grant Park that afternoon, a march was joined by delegates and McCarthy supporters but was stopped at 18th Street and Michigan Avenue by the National Guard.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Arrests were followed by tear gas and mace, while marchers chanted "The whole world is watching" and retreated to Grant Park.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In the park, demonstrators sang *God Bless America*, *This Land Is Your Land*, and *The Star-Spangled Banner*, and waved "V" symbols above their heads, asking soldiers to join in.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Phil Ochs sang "I Ain't Marchin' Any More", and demonstrators chanted "join us" softly.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Five hours later, police officers raided a party organized by McCarthy workers in the Hilton hotel, and beat them viciously.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] According to the McCarthy workers, all telephones on their floor had been disconnected a half hour before, and they had no way to call for help.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Department of Justice, the House Committee on Un-American Activities, and the presidentially appointed National Commission on the Causes and Prevention of Violence all responded with investigations of the violence.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Within days, the Daley administration issued the first report, blaming the violence on "outside agitators", described as "revolutionaries" who came to Chicago "for the avowed purpose of a hostile confrontation with law enforcement".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The Department of Justice report, however, found no grounds for prosecution of demonstrators, and Attorney General Ramsey Clark asked the U.S. attorney in Chicago to investigate possible civil rights violations by Chicago police.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] In Mayor Daley's report, a list of 152 officers wounded in Wednesday's melee was presented.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Their wounds ranged from an officer's split fingernail to an officer's infra-orbital fracture of the left eye.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Although the precise number of injured protesters is unknown, Dr.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Quentin Young of the Medical Committee for Human Rights (MCHR) stated that most of the approximately 500 people treated in the streets suffered from minor injuries and the effects of tear gas.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] During the entirety of convention week, 101 civilians were treated for undisclosed injuries, by area hospitals, 45 of those on Wednesday night.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] On September 4, 1968, Milton Eisenhower, chair of the National Commission on the Causes and Prevention of Violence, announced that the commission would investigate the violence at the Chicago convention and report its findings to President Lyndon Johnson.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] A Chicago lawyer, Daniel Walker, headed the team of over 200 members, who interviewed more than 1,400 witnesses and studied FBI reports and film of the confrontations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The commission's Walker Report, named after its chair Daniel Walker, acknowledged that demonstrators had provoked the police and responded with violence of their own, but found that the "vast majority of the demonstrators were intent on expressing by peaceful means their dissent".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The American national news media, whose correspondents had been among the victims of police brutality at the convention, were at the forefront of criticism of the Chicago police.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] To the surprise of the news media, and many of the people who had witnessed the Chicago "police riot", the general public did not take their side.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Daley himself received "scores of letters", praising him and especially attacking the press and demonstrators.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The jury delivered a verdict on February 18, 1970.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The trial "illuminated the deepening schisms in a country torn apart by the Vietnam War, tectonic cultural shifts and attempts by the Nixon Administration to quash peaceful antiwar dissent and protest".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] The trial, the defendants, and their attorneys gained much publicity and were depicted during and after the trial in a variety of art forms, including film, music, and theater.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Indignity, theater and hijinks during the event included presiding Judge Julius Hoffman ordering Bobby Seale to be bound, gagged, and chained to a chair, for refusing to obey the Judge's contempt citations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Over 100 witnesses were called by the defense, including singers Phil Ochs, Judy Collins, Arlo Guthrie, and Country Joe McDonald; comedian Dick Gregory; writers Norman Mailer and Allen Ginsberg; and activists Timothy Leary and Jesse Jackson.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] On May 11, 1972, the panel dismissed some contempt charges against the lawyers, and reversed all of the other contempt convictions for retrial with a different judge.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] On November 21, 1972, all of the criminal convictions were reversed by a United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit panel.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-democratic-national-convention-protests] Seven police officers were charged with assault and one police officer was charged with perjury, all were acquitted or had their case dismissed.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] A group of black organizations in Miami called for "a mass rally of concerned Black people," to take place on August 7, 1968, at the Vote Power building in Liberty City, a black neighborhood.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] Sponsors were the Vote Power League, the Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC), the Congress of Racial Equality (CORE), the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC), and numerous smaller organizations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] After a white reporter was forcibly ejected from the "Blacks Only" rally, Miami police responded with five cars and a carbine unit, which exacerbated tensions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] A white man in a car brandishing a "Wallace for President" bumper sticker attempted to drive through the vicinity.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] As he passed the Vote Power building, his automobile was met with a barrage of stones and bottles and crashed into another car.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] The driver fled on foot, and his car was overturned and set on fire.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] Vandals ransacked white-owned businesses in Liberty City's commercial district.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] Police eventually quelled the outbreak with tear gas.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] Florida governor Claude Kirk and SCLC president Ralph Abernathy, both attending the Republican National Convention, and Metro-Dade County mayor Chuck Hall arrived and held a meeting with community spokesmen.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] No actions to resolve the black communities' issues were agreed on.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] The Governor suggested that they continue the discussion at 11 AM the following morning.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] When, the following day, Kirk and local authorities only sent emissaries and did not appear themselves, larger-scale violence broke out.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] Rioters stoned police, fire-bombed area markets, and looted white-owned shops.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] Miami officials requested assistance from the Florida Highway Patrol, which used a cloud of tear gas dispensed by a modified version of an insect-control machine to restore order.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] That afternoon Miami police, responding to what they thought was sniper fire, killed two residents and left a fourteen-year-old boy with a bullet through his chest.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] Police, fearing that the unrest would spread to the Overtown neighborhood, shot and killed an unarmed man there as well.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] The Florida National Guard was called out, and a dusk-to-dawn curfew was imposed.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-miami-riot] 800 National Guard and 200 sheriff deputies restored order, and heavy rains the next day ended the riot.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A series of major student, intellectual and other protests against the ruling Polish United Workers' Party of the Polish People's Republic took place in Poland in March 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The crisis led to the suppression of student strikes by security forces in all major academic centres across the country and the subsequent repression of the Polish dissident movement.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] It was also accompanied by mass emigration following an antisemitic (branded "anti-Zionist") campaign waged by the minister of internal affairs, General Mieczysław Moczar, with the approval of First Secretary Władysław Gomułka of the Polish United Workers' Party (PZPR).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The protests overlapped with the events of the Prague Spring in neighboring Czechoslovakia – raising new hopes of democratic reforms among the intelligentsia.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The Czechoslovak unrest culminated in the Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia on 20 August 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The anti-Zionist campaign began in 1967, and was carried out in conjunction with the USSR's withdrawal of all diplomatic relations with Israel after the Six-Day War, but also involved a power struggle within the PZPR itself.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In carefully staged public displays of support, factory workers across Poland were assembled to publicly denounce Zionism.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] At least 13,000 Poles of Jewish origin emigrated in 1968–1972 as a result of being fired from their positions and various other forms of harassment.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The political turmoil of the late 1960s was exemplified in the West by increasingly violent protests against the Vietnam War and included numerous instances of protest and revolt, especially among students, that reverberated across Europe in 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The movement was reflected in the Eastern Bloc by the events of the Prague Spring, beginning 5 January 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A wave of protests in Czechoslovakia marked the high point of a broader series of dissident social mobilization.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] According to Ivan Krastev, the 1968 movement in Western Europe, emphasizing individual sovereignty, was fundamentally different from that in the Eastern Bloc, concerned primarily with national sovereignty.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In Poland, a growing crisis having to do with communist party control over universities, the literary community, and intellectuals in general, marked the mid-1960s.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Those persecuted for political activism on campus included Jacek Kuroń, Karol Modzelewski, Adam Michnik and Barbara Toruńczyk, among others.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A decade earlier, Poland was a scene of the Poznań 1956 protests and the Polish October events.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The events of 1967 and Polish communist leaders' necessity to follow the Soviet lead altered the relatively benign relations between People's Poland and Israel.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The combination of international and domestic factors gave rise in Poland to a campaign of hate against purported internal enemies, among whom the Jews would become the most salient target.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] As the Israeli–Arab Six-Day War started on 5 June 1967, the Polish Politburo met the following day and made policy determinations, declaring condemnation of "Israel's aggression" and full support for the "just struggle of the Arab countries".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] First Secretary Władysław Gomułka and Prime Minister Józef Cyrankiewicz went to Moscow on 9 June for a Middle East conference of communist leaders.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The participants deliberated in a depressing atmosphere.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The decisions made included the Warsaw Pact's continuation of military and financial support for the Arab states and the breaking of diplomatic relations with Israel, in which only Romania refused to participate.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A media campaign commenced in Poland and was soon followed by "anti-Israeli imperialism" rallies held in various towns and places of employment.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Gomułka did not issue a call for anti-Jewish personnel purges, but the so-called "anti-Zionist" campaign got underway anyway, supported by his close associates Zenon Kliszko and Ignacy Loga-Sowiński.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] It was eagerly amplified by General Mieczysław Moczar, minister of internal affairs, by some military leaders who had long been waiting for an opportunity to "settle with the Jews", and by other officials.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A list of 382 "Zionists" was presented at the ministry on 28 June and the purge slowly developed, beginning with Jewish generals and other high-ranking officers of the Polish armed forces.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] About 150 Jewish military officers were fired in 1967–1968, including Czesław Mankiewicz, national air defense chief.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Minister of Defense Marian Spychalski tried to defend Mankiewicz and by doing so compromised his own position.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The Ministry of Internal Affairs renewed its proposal to ban the Jewish organizations from receiving foreign contributions from the American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] This time, unlike on previous occasions, the request was quickly granted by the Secretariat of the PZPR's Central Committee and the well-developed Jewish social, educational and cultural organized activities in Poland faced stiff reductions or even practical liquidation.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] About 200 people lost their jobs and were removed from the party top leadership in 1967, including Leon Kasman, chief editor of *Trybuna Ludu*, the party's main daily newspaper.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Kasman was Moczar's hated rival from the time of the war when he arrived from the Soviet Union and was parachuted into Poland.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] After March 1968, when Moczar's ministry was finally given the freehand it had long sought, 40 employees were fired from the editorial staff of the Polish Scientific Publishers (PWN).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] This major state publishing house had produced a number of volumes of the official *Great Universal Encyclopedia*.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Moczar and others protested in the fall of 1967 the supposedly unbalanced treatment of World War II issues, namely stressing Jewish martyrdom and the disproportionate numbers of Jews killed in Nazi extermination camps.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] On 19 June 1967, Gomułka warned in his speech: "We don't want an establishment of a fifth column in our country".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The sentence was deleted from a published version, but such views he repeated and developed further in successive speeches, for example on 19 March 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] On 27 June 1967, the first secretary characterized Romania's position as shameful, predicted production of nuclear arms by Israel and spoke generally of consequences faced by people who had "two souls and two fatherlands".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Following Gomułka's anti-Israel and anti-Jewish rhetoric, the security services began screening officials of Jewish origin and looking for 'hidden Zionists' in Polish institutions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The outbreak of the March 1968 unrest was seemingly triggered by a series of events in Warsaw, but in reality, it was a culmination of trends accumulating in Poland over several years.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The economic situation was deteriorating and a drastic increase in the prices of meat came into effect in 1967.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In 1968, the market was destabilized further by rumors of upcoming currency exchange and the ensuing panic.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Higher norms were enforced for industrial productivity with wages reduced at the same time.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] First Secretary Gomułka was afraid of all changes.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The increasingly heavy censorship stifled intellectual life, the boredom of stagnation and the mood of hopelessness (lack of career prospects) generated social conflict.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The disparity between the expectations raised by the Polish October movement of 1956 and the actuality of the "real socialism" life of the 1960s led to mounting frustration.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] At the end of January 1968, after its poor reception by the Central Committee of the ruling PZPR, the government authorities banned the performance of a Romantic play by Adam Mickiewicz called *Dziady* (written in 1824), directed by Kazimierz Dejmek at the National Theatre, Warsaw.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] It was claimed that the play contained Russophobic and anti-Soviet references and represented an unduly pro-religion stance.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] *Dziady* had been staged 11 times, the last time on 30 January.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The ban was followed by a demonstration after the final performance, which resulted in numerous police detentions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Dejmek was expelled from the party and subsequently fired from the National Theatre.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] He left Poland and returned in 1973, to continue directing theatrical productions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In mid-February, a petition signed by 3,000 people (or over 4,200, depending on the source) protesting the censorship of *Dziady* was submitted to parliament by student protester Irena Lasota.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Gathered for an extraordinary meeting on 29 February with over 400 attendees, the Warsaw chapter of the Polish Writers' Union condemned the ban and other encroachments on free speech rights.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A crowd of some 500 (or about 1,000) students rallying at the university on 8 March was attacked violently by organized "worker activists" (probably plainclothes police) and by police in uniform.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Nonetheless, other institutions of higher learning in Warsaw joined the protest a day later.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Dariusz Gawin of the Polish Academy of Sciences pointed out that the March 1968 events have been mythologized in subsequent decades beyond their modest original aims, under the lasting influence of former members of *Komandosi*, a left-wing student political activity group.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] During the 1968 crisis, the dissident academic circles produced very little in terms of written accounts or programs.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] They experienced a moral shock because of propaganda misrepresentations of their intentions and actions and the unexpectedly violent repressions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] They also experienced an ideological shock, caused by the reaction of the authorities (aggression) and society (indifference) to their idealistic attempts to bring about revolutionary reform in the Polish People's Republic.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The alienation of the reform movement from the ostensibly socialist system (and their own leftist views) had begun.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The students were naïve in terms of practical politics, but their leaders professed strongly leftist convictions, expressed in brief proclamations distributed in 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Following the spirit of the 1964 "revisionist" manifesto by Karol Modzelewski and Jacek Kuroń, they demanded respect for the ideals of the Marxist–Leninist "dictatorship of the proletariat" and principles of socialism.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The protesting students sang "The Internationale" anthem.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The storming of Warsaw University by the (fake) factory worker activists thus came as a total surprise to the students.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The participants of the 8 March rally were met with violent beatings from ORMO volunteer reserve and ZOMO riot squads just as they were about to go home.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The disproportionately brutal reaction of the security forces appeared to many observers to be a provocation perpetrated to aggravate the unrest and facilitate further rounds of repression, in the self-interest of political leaders.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A comparable demonstration originated on 9 March at the Warsaw University of Technology and was also followed by confrontations with the police and arrests.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Kuroń, Modzelewski and Michnik were imprisoned again and a majority of the *Komandosi* members were detained.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In later accounts, however, the founding mythology of Poland's civil society movement (the late 1970s) and then of the establishment of the new democratic-liberal Poland would obliterate the socialist, leftist and revolutionary aspects of the March 1968 movement.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Within a few days protests spread to Kraków, Lublin, Gliwice, Katowice, and Łódź (from 11 March), Wrocław, Gdańsk, and Poznań (12 March).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The frequent demonstrations at the above locations were brutally suppressed by the police.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Mass student strikes took place in Wrocław on 14–16 March, Kraków on 14–20 March, and Opole.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A student committee at Warsaw University (11 March) and an inter-university committee in Kraków (13 March) were formed; attempts to organize were also made in Łódź and Wrocław.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Efforts aimed at getting industrial workers involved, for example, employees of the state enterprises in Gdańsk, Wrocław and Kraków's Nowa Huta produced no tangible effects.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] But on 15 March in Gdańsk, 20,000 students and workers marched and fought several types of security forces totalling 3,700 men, into the late evening.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] University students comprised less than 25% of those arrested for participating in opposition activities in March and April 1968 (their numerical predominance in the movement was a part of the subsequent myth, wrote historian Łukasz Kamiński).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The leading role in the spreading countrywide street protests was played by young factory workers and secondary school students.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A media campaign besmirching targeted groups and individuals was conducted from 11 March.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The Stalinist and Jewish ("non-Polish") roots of the supposed instigators were "exposed" and most printed press participated in the propagation of slander, with the notable exceptions of *Polityka* and *Tygodnik Powszechny*.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Mass "spontaneous" rallies at places of employment and in squares of major cities took place.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The participants demanded "Students resume their studies, writers their writing", "Zionists go to Zion!", or threatened "We'll tear off the head of the anti-Polish hydra".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Silesian water will crush their bones ...".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Gierek introduced a new element during his speech: a statement of support for First Secretary Gomułka, who so far had been silent on the student protests, Zionism and other currently pressing issues.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] This initial reluctance of the top leadership to express their position ended with a speech by Gomułka on 19 March.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] He eliminated the possibility of government negotiations with the strikers, extinguishing the participants' hope for a quick favorable settlement.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Gomułka's speech, delivered before three thousand ("outstanding during the difficult days") party activists, was full of anti-intelligentsia accusations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The party management realized, he made it clear, that it was too early to fully comprehend and evaluate the nature and scope of the present difficulties.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The first secretary attempted to pacify the growing antisemitic wave, asserting that most citizens of Jewish origin were loyal to Poland and were not a threat.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Loyalty to Poland and socialism, not ethnicity, was the only criterion, the party valued highly those who had contributed and was opposed to any phenomena of antisemitic nature.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] It was understood that some people could feel ambivalent about where they belonged, and if some felt definitely more closely connected with Israel, Gomułka expected them to eventually emigrate.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] However, it may have been too late for such reasoned arguments and the carefully screened audience did not react positively: their collective display of hatred was shown on national television.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Gomułka's remarks (reviewed, corrected and approved in advance by members of the Politburo and the Central Committee) were criticized a few days later at the meeting of first secretaries of the provincial party committees and the anti-Zionist campaign continued unabated.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The internal bulletin of Mieczysław Moczar's Ministry of Internal Affairs spoke of a lack of clear declaration on Zionism on Gomułka's part and of "public hiding of criminals".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Such criticism of the top party leader was unheard of and indicated the increasing influence and determination of Moczar's faction.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The purges and attempts to resolve the power struggle at top echelons of the party entered their accelerated phase.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The mass protest movement and the repressions continued throughout March and April.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The revolt was met with the dissolution of entire academic departments, the expulsion of thousands of students and many sympathizing faculty members (including Zygmunt Bauman, Leszek Kołakowski and Stefan Żółkiewski), arrests and court trials.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] National coordination by the students was attempted through a 25 March meeting in Wrocław; most of its attendees were jailed by the end of April.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] On 28 March, students at the University of Warsaw reacted to the firing of prominent faculty by adopting the Declaration of the Student Movement, which presented an outline of mature systemic reforms for Poland.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The document formulated a new framework for opposition activities and established a conceptual precedent for the future Solidarity opposition movement postulates.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The authorities responded by eliminating several university departments and enlisting many students in the military.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The student protest activities, planned for 22 April, were prevented by the arrest campaign conducted in Warsaw, Kraków and Wrocław.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] At least 2,725 people were arrested between 7 March and 6 April.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] According to internal government reports, the suppression was effective, although students were still able to disrupt the May Day ceremonies in Wrocław.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Except for the relatively few well-recognized protest leaders, the known participants of the 1968 revolt generally did not reappear in later waves of opposition movement in Poland.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] By mid-March, the protest campaign had spread to smaller towns.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The distribution of fliers was reported in one hundred towns in March, forty in April, and, despite numerous arrests, continued even during the later months.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Street demonstrations occurred in several localities in March.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In different cities, the arrests and trials proceeded at a different pace, in part because of the discretion exercised by local authorities.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Gdańsk had by far the highest rate of both the "penal-administrative procedures" and the cases that actually went to courts.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The largest proportion of the arrested and detained nationwide during the March/April unrest belonged to the "workers" category.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A few dared to openly defend the students, including some writers, bishops, and the small parliamentary group of Catholic deputies *Znak*, led by Jerzy Zawieyski.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] *Znak* submitted an official interpellation on 11 March, addressed to the prime minister.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] They questioned the brutal anti-student interventions by the police and inquired about the government's intentions regarding the democratic demands of the students and of the "broad public opinion".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Prime Minister Józef Cyrankiewicz asserted that the Radio Free Europe used the *Znak* interpellation for its propaganda.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Other speakers claimed that the interpellation was primarily aimed at getting the hostile foreign interests involved in Poland's affairs.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Zawieyski spoke in a conciliatory tone, directing his comments and appealing to Gomułka and Zenon Kliszko, recognizing them as victims of the past (Stalinist) political persecution.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] He interpreted the recent beating by "unknown assailants" of Stefan Kisielewski, a Catholic publicist, as an attack on a representative of the Polish culture.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The party leaders responded by terminating Zawieyski's membership in the Polish Council of State, a collective head of state organ, and banning him from holding a political office in the future.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The participants in the public *Sejm* debate concentrated on attacking *Znak* and avoided altogether discussing the events and issues of the March protests or their suppression (the subjects of the interpellation).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The effectiveness of the ORMO interventions on university campuses and the eruption of further citizen discontent (see 1970 Polish protests) prompted the Ministry of Public Security to engage in massive expansion of this force, which at its peak in 1979 reached over 450,000 members.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In March 1968, the anti-Zionist campaign, loud propaganda and mass mobilization were greatly intensified.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The process of purging Jewish officials, ex-Stalinists, high-ranking rival communists and moral supporters of the current liberal opposition movement, was accelerated.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Roman Zambrowski, Stefan Staszewski, Edward Ochab, Adam Rapacki and Marian Spychalski were among the top echelon party leaders removed or neutralized.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Zambrowski, a Jewish veteran of the Polish communist movement, was singled out and purged from the party first (13 March), even though he had been politically inactive for several years and had nothing to do with the current crisis.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Former First Secretary Ochab resigned his several high offices to protest "against the antisemitic campaign".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] On 11 April 1968, the *Sejm* instituted changes in some major leadership positions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Spychalski, leaving the Ministry of Defense, replaced Ochab in the more titular role as the chairman of the Council of State.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Wojciech Jaruzelski became the new minister of defense.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Rapacki, another opponent of antisemitic purges, was replaced by Stefan Jędrychowski at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A new higher education statute was designed to give the government greater control over the academic environment.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Gomułka considered revisionism rather than "Zionism" to be the main "danger".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] According to historian Dariusz Stola, the first secretary, whose wife was Jewish, harbored no antisemitic prejudices.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] But he opportunistically and instrumentally allowed and accepted the anti-Jewish initiative of Minister Moczar and the secret services Moczar controlled.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Many Poles (irrespective of ethnic background) were accused of being Zionists.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] They were expelled from the party and/or had their careers terminated by policies that were cynical, prejudicial, or both.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Long (sometimes conducted over several days) party meetings and discussions took place at the end of March and in early April within various state institutions and enterprises.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] They dealt with the "Zionism" issue and were devoted to the identification of those responsible and guilty (within the institution's own ranks), their expulsion from the party and demands for their removal from the positions they held.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Attempts were made to steer the attention of the general public away from the student movement and advocacy for social reform, centered around the defense of freedom of speech for intellectuals and artists and the right to criticize the regime and its policies.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Moczar, the leader of the hardline Stalinist faction of the party, blamed the student protests on "Zionists" and used the protest activity as a pretext for a larger antisemitic campaign (officially described as "anti-Zionist") and party purges.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In reality, the student and intellectual protests were generally not related to Zionism or other Jewish issues.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The propagated idea of the "Zionist inspiration" of student rebellion originated in part from the presence of children of Jewish communists among those contesting the political order, including especially members of the *Komandosi* group.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] To augment their numbers, figures of speech such as the "Michniks, Szlajfers, Zambrowskis" were used.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The national strike call from Warsaw (13 March) opposed both antisemitism and Zionism.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] However, Gomułka warned that "Zionism and antisemitism are two sides of the same nationalist medal" and insisted that communism rejects all forms of nationalism.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] According to Gomułka, who rejected the Western allegations of antisemitism, "Official circles in the United States have involved themselves in the dirty anti-Polish campaign by making statements accusing Poland of antisemitism.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] We propose that the ruling circles in the United States check whether American citizens of Polish descent have ever had or have now the same opportunities that Polish citizens of Jewish descent have for good living conditions and education and for occupying positions of responsibility.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] By 1968 Gomułka, whose public relations skills were poor, was unpopular and had lost touch with the population he ruled.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Personnel changes, resisted by Gomułka, were generally desired and expected, and in the party, General Moczar was the alternative.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Large numbers of generally younger functionaries mobilized behind him, motivated by the potential opportunity to advance their stagnant careers.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Finding scapegoats (possibly by just claiming that someone was enthusiastic about the Israeli victory) and becoming their replacements meant in 1968 progress in that direction.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The Moczar faction's activity was one of the major factors that contributed to the 1968 uproar, but the overdue generational change within the party materialized fully only when Edward Gierek replaced Gomułka in December 1970.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Moczar himself campaigned ruthlessly in an ultimately failed attempt to become Gomułka's replacement or successor.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In a parliamentary speech on 11 April 1968, Prime Minister Cyrankiewicz spelled out the government's official position: "Loyalty to socialist Poland and imperialist Israel is not possible simultaneously. ...
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Whoever wants to face these consequences in the form of emigration will not encounter any obstacle." The departing had their Polish citizenship revoked.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Historian David Engel of the YIVO Institute wrote: "The Interior Ministry compiled a card index of all Polish citizens of Jewish origin, even those who had been detached from organized Jewish life for generations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Jews were removed from jobs in public service, including from teaching positions in schools and universities.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The propaganda equated Jewish origins with Zionist sympathies and thus disloyalty to communist Poland.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Antisemitic slogans were used in rallies.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Prominent Jews, supposedly of Zionist beliefs, including academics, managers and journalists, lost their jobs.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] According to the Polish state's Institute of National Remembrance (IPN), which investigated events that took place in 1968–69 in Łodź, "in each case the decision of dismissal was preceded by a party resolution about expelling from the party".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] According to Jonathan Ornstein, of the 3.5 million Polish Jews prior to World War II, 350,000 or fewer remained after the Holocaust.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Most survivors who claimed their Jewish nationality status at the end of World War II, including those who registered with the Central Committee of Polish Jews in 1945, had emigrated from postwar Poland already in its first years of existence.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] According to David Engel's estimates, of the fewer than 281,000 Jews present in Poland at different times before July 1946, only about 90,000 were left in the country by the middle of 1947.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Fewer than 80,000 remained by 1951, when the government prohibited emigration to Israel.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] An additional 30,000 arrived from the Soviet Union in 1957, but almost 50,000, typically people actively expressing Jewish identity, left Poland in 1957–1959, under Gomułka and with his government's encouragement.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] As a group, they had become increasingly assimilated and secular and had well-developed and functioning Jewish secular institutions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Of the Jews who stayed in Poland, many did so for political and career reasons.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Their situation changed after the 1967 Arab–Israeli war and the 1968 Polish academic revolt when the Jews were used as scapegoats by the warring party factions and pressured to emigrate *en masse* once more.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] According to Engel, some 25,000 Jews left Poland during the 1968–70 period, leaving only between 5,000 and 10,000 Jews in the country.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Some 11,200 Jews from Poland immigrated to Israel during 1968 and 1969.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] From the end of World War II, the Soviet-imposed government in Poland, lacking strong popular support, found it expedient to depend disproportionately on Jews for performing clerical and administrative jobs and many Jews rose to high positions within the political and internal security ranks.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Consequently, as noted by historian Michael C.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Steinlauf – "their group profile ever more closely resembled the mythic Żydokomuna" (see also Jewish Bolshevism).
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] For complex historical reasons, Jews held many positions of repressive authority under the post-war Polish communist administrations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In March 1968, some of those officials became the center of an organized campaign to equate Jewish origins with Stalinist sympathies and crimes.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The political purges, often ostensibly directed at functionaries of the Stalinist era, affected all Polish Jews regardless of background.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Prior to the 1967–68 events, Polish-Jewish relations had been a taboo subject in communist Poland.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Available information was limited to the dissemination of shallow and distorted official versions of historical events, while much of the traditional social antisemitic resentment was brewing under the surface, despite the scarcity of Jewish targets.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Popular antisemitism of the post-war years was closely linked to anticommunist and anti-Soviet attitudes and as such was resisted by the authorities.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The outwardly Stalinist character of the campaign was paradoxically combined with anti-Stalinist and anti-Żydokomuna rhetoric.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The media "exposed" various past and present Jewish conspiracies directed against socialist Poland, often using prejudicial Jewish stereotypes, which supposedly added up to a grand Jewish anti-Polish scheme.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] West German-Israeli and American-Zionist anti-Poland blocs were also "revealed".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In Poland, it was claimed, the old Jewish Stalinists were secretly preparing their own return to power, to thwart the Polish October gains.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The small number of Jews remaining in Poland were subjected to unbearable pressures generated by the state monopolistic media, often dominated by sympathizers of Minister Moczar.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Many Jews and non-Jews were smeared and removed by their local Basic Party Organizations (POP), after which they had to be fired from their jobs.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Many professionals and non-members of the party fell victim as well.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Most of the last wave (1968–69) of emigrants chose destinations other than Israel, which contradicted the government's claim of their pro-Israeli devotion.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Disproportionately in Polish society, they represented highly educated, professional, and accomplished people.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Some communist party activists had previously perceived this factor as an undue "density" of Jews in positions of importance, a remnant of Stalinist times, which resulted in calls for their marginalization and removal from the country.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Over a thousand former hardline Stalinists of Jewish origin left Poland in and after 1968, among them former prosecutor Helena Wolińska-Brus and judge Stefan Michnik.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The IPN had investigated Stalinist crimes committed by some of the March 1968 emigrants including Michnik, who settled in Sweden, and Wolińska-Brus, who resided in the United Kingdom.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Both were accused of being an "accessory to a court murder".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Applications were made for their extradition based on the European Arrest Warrants.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Between 1961 and 1967, the average rate of Jewish emigration from Poland was 500–900 persons per year.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In 1968, a total of 3,900 Jews applied to leave the country.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Between January and August 1969, the number of emigrating Jews was almost 7,300, all according to records of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The security organs maintained comprehensive data on persons with "family background in Israel" or of Jewish origin, including those dismissed from their positions and those who did not hold any official positions but applied for emigration to Israel.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] On 11 April 1968, Secretary of the Central Committee Artur Starewicz gave Gomułka a comprehensive letter, in which he pointed out the destructiveness of the demagoguery, anti-Jewish obsession and other aspects of the campaign.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In late April Gomułka realized that the campaign he allowed had outlived its usefulness and was getting out of control; many participants became overzealous and complaints from various quarters multiplied.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] However, ending it and restoring normal party control and discipline took several weeks of repeated warnings and other efforts.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] On 24 June, Gomułka sharply criticized Stefan Olszowski, the party propaganda chief and the role played by the PAX publications.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Both were heavily involved in the "anti-Zionist", but also "nationalistic" media campaign from 11 March.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] On 1 July, Leopold Domb (Leopold Trepper), former chairman of the Sociocultural Association of Jews (in Poland), wrote a letter to his party boss Gomułka.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Domb bitterly complained of the progressive liquidation of the thousand years of Polish-Jewish civilizational achievement and listed numerous instances of such destruction of society and culture taking place in contemporary communist Poland.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] On 5 July, Gomułka acknowledged "certain problems" with the Ministry of Internal Affairs and announced the removal of Minister Moczar from the cabinet position, which disconnected him from his power base at that department.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Moczar's sidelining was presented as a promotion: he became secretary of the Central Committee and a deputy member of the Politburo.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] "Comrade Moczar is a disciplined man and he'll do as he is told", was how Gomułka saw the resolution.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Gomułka's ability to decisively dismantle the Internal Affairs' anti-Jewish smear campaign and punish its perpetrators (for challenging the party leadership) shows that he could have done so earlier, had he chosen to act in a timely manner.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] During the XII Plenum of the Central Committee (8–9 July), Zenon Kliszko officially closed the "anti-Zionist" campaign.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Internal attacks and obstruction within the party, the military and the security services (SB), now directed against Gomułka and Kliszko, continued for some time.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In reality, SB's "anti-Zionist" activities were never completely abandoned.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] During 1970–80, General Jaruzelski demoted to the rank of private 1,348 Jewish officers who had emigrated, not only around 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Such continued activities were conducted in secret.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The media propaganda machine was by early summer preoccupied with denouncing the Prague Spring.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In August, the Polish People's Army participated in the Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The Fifth Congress of the PZPR took place in November, under Gomułka' s active lead.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The gathering, numerically dominated by the supporters of Moczar, was maneuvered into complying with Gomułka faction's personnel decisions.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The party now had 2.1 million members (only 40% were workers), after the recent purging of over 230,000.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The Jewish activists were gone, but many other veterans remained, as the generational change in the communist leadership was beginning to take place.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Gomułka was able to rule with his few close associates until December 1970, but his prestige suffered in Poland, abroad, and among the Soviet and other Eastern Bloc leaders.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A consequence of the protest events and their repercussions was the alienation of the regime from the leftist intelligentsia, who were disgusted at the official promotion of antisemitism and the adoption of nationalistic rhetoric.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Many Polish intellectuals opposed the government campaign, often openly.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Another effect was the activity by Polish emigrants to the West in organizations that encouraged opposition within Poland.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The alienation of Polish intelligentsia had a long afterlife and eventually contributed to the downfall of the communist dictatorship: the 1968 events were a turning point in the ideological evolution of those who would challenge the system in the years to come.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Jacek Kuroń, for example, twice a party member and an activist imprisoned for his participation in the 1968 events, later played important roles in the Workers' Defence Committee and the Solidarity workers' movement.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The events of 1968, preceded by those in 1956 and followed by those of 1970, 1976 and 1980, showed that Poland, with its strong nationalist traditions, a civil society, and the powerful Catholic Church, was the source of instability and weakness in the Eastern Bloc.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The dangers presented to the PZPR by the "reactionary" coalition of 1968, against which some had already warned back then, turned out not to be imaginary, but their realization took another two decades.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] The antisemitic, anti-intellectual and anti-student campaign damaged Poland's reputation, particularly in the West.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Despite the worldwide condemnation of the March 1968 repressions, for many years the communist governments would not admit the antisemitic nature of the "anti-Zionist" campaign, though some newspapers published critical articles.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In February and March 1988, the Polish communist government announced official apologies for the antisemitic excesses of 1968: first in Israel at a conference on Polish Jewry, and then in a statement printed in *Trybuna Ludu*.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] A Central Committee report even suggested an introduction of dual citizenship to improve relations with the Jews who left Poland.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] After the fall of the communist rule, the *Sejm* in 1998 issued an official condemnation of the antisemitism of the March 1968 events.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In 2000, President Aleksander Kwaśniewski gave his own apology in front of a group of Jewish students "as the president of Poland and as a Pole".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] On the 30th anniversary of their departures, a memorial plaque was placed at Warszawa Gdańska train station, from which most of the exiled Poles took a train to Vienna.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] In March 2018 Polish President Andrzej Duda said "We are sorry you're not here today" and "those were deported then and the families of those who were killed – I want to say, please forgive Poland for that" in relation to the 20,000 Jews expelled or forced to flee in 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] However, Duda said that his generation was not responsible for the actions of the past communist administration.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-polish-political-crisis] Duda's distinction between the past Polish government whom he framed as culpable, and Polish citizens whom he framed as innocent, was seen as a non-apology by critics.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] The **1968 Red Square demonstration** (Russian: Демонстра́ция 25 а́вгуста 1968 го́да) took place in Moscow on 25 August 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] It was a protest by eight demonstrators against the invasion of Czechoslovakia on the night of 20–21 August 1968 by the Soviet Union and its Warsaw Pact allies, crushing the Prague Spring, the challenge to centralised planning and censorship by communist leader Alexander Dubček.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] The protest took place at the Lobnoye Mesto (Place of Proclamation) on Red Square next to the Kremlin, to avoid any accusation of a violation of public order.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] It was a nonviolent, sit-down demonstration.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] However, all but one of the protestors were quickly and roughly arrested by police and plainclothes KGB men.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] Within a few minutes, seven of the protesters were assaulted, brutally beaten and loaded into cars by KGB operatives.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] The Czechoslovak flag was broken, and the placards were confiscated.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] Since Natalya Gorbanevskaya had recently given birth, she was not made to stand trial.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] The other protesters convinced 21-year-old Tatiana Baeva to declare that she had been at the scene by accident, and she was released soon after.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] The KGB failed to find out which protester was holding which banner; therefore, all the banners were attributed to each protester, except for Tatiana Baeva, who was released.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] The banners were branded by the KGB as "anti-Soviet".
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] During the investigation and trial, the defence revealed several inconsistencies in the accusations.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] One of the eyewitnesses declared that he saw protesters leaving the GUM, a large store in the vicinity, even though this store is closed on Sundays.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] Additionally, all eyewitnesses happened to be from the same military division, even though they all claimed that they ended up on Red Square accidentally.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] However, these inconsistencies were not taken into account during the trial.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] None of the demonstrators pleaded guilty.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] Vadim Delaunay and Vladimir Dremlyuga were sentenced to three years in a penal colony.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] Victor Fainberg, who had his teeth knocked out during the arrest, did not appear in court but was sent to a psychiatric prison.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] Larisa Bogoraz was sentenced to four years of exile to a remote Siberian settlement in the Irkutsk Region.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] Konstantin Babitsky was sentenced to three years of exile.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] Pavel Litvinov was sentenced to five years' exile.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] Natalya Gorbanevskaya was released the same day but later sent to a psychiatric prison.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] In his "Attorney's waltz" singer and rights activist Yuliy Kim claimed that the sentences had been decided before the trial.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] In another song, "Ilyich", Kim mentions Yuri Andropov's and Leonid Brezhnev's anger at the demonstration, and refers to three of the protestors by name -- Pavel Litvinov, Natalya Gorbanevskaya and Larisa Bogoraz.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] The story of the August 1968 demonstration is recounted in the 2005 documentary *They Chose Freedom*.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] In 1990 (following the Velvet Revolution), seven of the protesters were awarded honorary citizenship of Prague.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] During the conflict in South Ossetia, August 2008, the former president of the Czech Republic, Václav Havel, expressed his sympathies for the protesters of 1968.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] Czech Premier Mirek Topolánek recognized the heroism of the protesters with awards.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] There was no recognition on the part of the Russian government.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] On 24 August 2008, the similar demonstration with the slogan For your freedom and ours was held in the same place.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] On 25 August 2013, the 45th anniversary of the demonstration, Gorbanevskaya and several of her friends recreated the original protest, again featuring the "For your freedom and ours" banner.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] Ten participants (among them Delaunay's son Sergey) were arrested almost immediately and taken to a police station.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] They were soon arraigned and released pending court appearance on charges of failing to secure prior permission for a political rally, a misdemeanor under current Russian law.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] In 2018, three participants at another repeat demonstration were arrested.
[src:1968-red-square-demonstration/1968-red-square-demonstration] On February 5, 2025, Tatiana Baeva, who was one of the participant members of the 1968 Red Square demonstration died at the age of 77.
